7 (4) (a) Except as provided in subsection (5), a health care professional or physician may be found
8 liable under subsection (1) for an injury caused by the following treatments or the after-effects of the following
9 treatments provided to a female patient to address the patient's perception that the patient's gender or sex is
10 not female:
11 (i) surgical procedures, including a vaginectomy, hysterectomy, oophorectomy, ovariectomy,
12 reconstruction of the urethra, metoidioplasty, phalloplasty, scrotoplasty, implantation of erection or testicular
13 protheses, subcutaneous mastectomy, voice surgery, or pectoral implants;
14 (ii) supraphysiologic doses of testosterone or other androgens; or
15 (iii) puberty blockers such as GnRH agonists or other synthetic drugs that suppress the production
16 of estrogen and progesterone to delay or suppress pubertal development in female minors.
17 (b) Except as provided in subsection (5), a health care professional or physician may be found
18 liable under subsection (1) for an injury caused by the following treatments or the after-effects of the following
19 treatments provided to a male patient to address the patient's perception that the patient's gender or sex is not
20 male:
21 (i) surgical procedures, including a penectomy, orchiectomy, vaginoplasty, clitoroplasty,
22 vulvoplasty, augmentation mammoplasty, facial feminization surgery, voice surgery, thyroid cartilage reduction,
23 or gluteal augmentation;
24 (ii) supraphysiologic doses of estrogen; or
25 (iii) puberty blockers such as GnRH agonists or other synthetic drugs that suppress the production
26 of testosterone or delay or suppress pubertal development in male minors.
27 (5) The medical treatments listed in subsections (4)(a) and (4)(b) may be the basis of a claim
28 under subsection (1) only when knowingly provided to address a female patient's perception that the patient's
